title: Social and Emotional Development
subject: Infant and Toddler Early Learning and Development Standards (2024-)

document.title: Infant and Toddler Maine Early Learning and Development Standards (Infant Toddler MELDS)

9E6BC9942209422F9DCC659B63EE6700.description:
Engages in reciprocal play such as run
and chase or offer and receive.

09D9110A526A49B18AA2DC7E2B3D486B.description:
Shows concern for a peer who is in
distress.

2E0206E4B9014B7B9F18470956D10DDA.description:
Engages in joint exploration and has
begun associative play; for example,
attempts to build a block tower with a
friend or can wait a short time for “my
turn”.

168A12359578403DAD022E90843EF29E.description:
Exhibits sadness when a favorite friend
is not at school; “When you miss your
friend here at school, she misses you
too”.

C4C22B9DDA424AC6A595B63B5A50528E.description:
Expresses an interest in playing with a
particular child.

93C84D9B1F934222BCE96FEDCBEBAE1C.description:
Engages in social pretend play with
one or two friends and take on roles; for
example, pretends to be a dog while a
friend pretends to be the owner.

D90002D7646F477B8CFCCD4798262647.description:
Knows the family members of frequent
playmates.

2BBA2A3ECFE44D4B9B5584568AA03189.description:
Knows the names of peers when they
are referred to.

8E96DB7368EF4566BC5AE71063036B62.description:
Begins to show preference among play
partners, often hugging or touching
them.

46614FA57957484EBD181A3798DB5853.description:
Influences and responds to a peer’s
behavior in a simplistic manner; for
example, handing a playmate a doll.

919E51392A0740C58C097E19E166C870.description:
Participates in spontaneous interactions
with peers and exhibits enjoyment.

AFDF2BA8B9F24017B52656152D8B78A5.description:
Matches emotions with a peer’s
emotions.

F417A6D54AAB4370A45EF71D8459B546.description:
Tries to get the attention of another child
by smiling or babbling to him/her.

ED5A29B1B84541FEBAB158BFAB429866.description:
Laughs when an older sibling or peer
makes a funny face.

282EC5C1847146C882F95F00F68AEAE9.description:
Reaches out to touch eyes or hair of a
peer

A122A8B1EB4E46D8BD977F8C8E348F6D.description:
Notices a crying peer with a serious
expression.

64058C5BC3C34481A5B0BB8A76046161.description: Turns to the voice of an older sibling.

E74642EE8F914A1BB62F5A505F09CBF9.description:
Begins to follow simple instructions or
guidance of a caregiver.

6E49D94F47ED4C32994EF44D2994E255.description:
Uses adult as a resource through words
or actions; for example, asks a caregiver
for a cracker or for help getting jacket on.

0F8B69FEA4F44A07A0222EC92E782738.description:
Gesturing for one more hug as a parent
is leaving for work.

6E4830D0E7B34743B8E05241F1D63EB3.description:
Tries to influence adult behavior; for
example, brings favorite book and
expresses “One more?” even though she
has just heard “We are all done; time for
a nap”.

B2AFB8D4C7CB43CFAD0B327F2F0F2411.description:
Cries and looks for special caregiver after
falling.

AABE42FF693F41EAA9D3DFFFE351DDF0.description:
Seeks attention of a special caregiver
and communicates “Watch me!” before
proudly displaying a new skill.

1022574DD26D496BB14EC5F204E8A8D4.description:
Imitates sequence of events after seeing
the sequence completed by a caregiving
adult; for example, read a story to a doll
or put a teddy to bed.

7903EC24212D40E58F873FF086C57D7B.description:
When distressed child seeks to be
physically close to primary caregiver.

226EBA530F774E86808B54772E17D3CF.description:
Plays away from the primary caregiver
and then moves close to him or her from
time to time to check in.

824AAF94AB7B40BF9CD05086A67CA48B.description:
Feels secure to explore environment in
presence of primary caregiving adult.

009C5637E85E4824BCAAF80605A1B45D.description:
Exhibits separation anxiety, cries briefly
when separated from parent or caregiver.

5359CF7C7D3741DFA904D290EF32811D.description:
Distinguishes between familiar and
unfamiliar adults.

FFDB5B017E6D48ED905FE71D62147714.description:
Forms attachment with primary
caregiver; more easily soothed, studies
the face, attends longer to caregiver’s
facial expressions.

53BF1B3F99454286A8511B39161CF008.description:
Responds to being held: Calming down,
molding of the body to the caregiver.

BC5A867079D14D7AB9F81EC652FBC0CA.description:
Shows preference for familiar adult, lifts
arms to be picked up by special adult;
squealing and kicking when familiar
adult appears.

1ABE0257348B4F4B9DEE0C27174A2673.description:
Is more easily soothed by sound of
primary caregiver’s voice than unfamiliar
voice.

312CB132D6334800A62D0A195B3CAD0E.description:
Seeks comfort from caring adult by
crying and looking for him or her.

F21F5E4FEDC34AA99A4EF9CAB66E1E82.description:
Uses evaluative words to talk about self,
“Me good girl?”

5C7C177103B646F18F19E53F745FF02B.description:
Wants to experience the world on
own terms; for example, avoids messy
materials.

F7CFCD4E5E2F4F6784D8796A8E5FD690.description:
Respect toddlers’ valid opinion of saying
no.

C8D8C60E28234141A9971F2AE10B7FF0.description:
Communicates, “I do it!” or “No” when
caregiver or parent tries to help.

5FCCD10CED204B62B708A88E3BD7B954.description:
Uses adjectives to refer to self, for
example:, “Me big”.

723BB3176CFD41D096BF50A5B91C2759.description:
Begins to make comparisons between
self and others; for example:, “Tommy is
boy like me."

040427F787924F189C8CB48A6B73FF79.description:
Identifies self by gender, for example:, “I
boy”.

FDD25A18383F4294AFC5BC69AA046207.description:
Says own name when asked and names
others in family

BC4A069E5D484BFAB61602054F35036E.description:
Recognizes own image in the mirror or
photo and understands that it is self.

485BA82FEB03468F9E8EB3305CE58C12.description:
Shows signs of mastery; for example:,
laughs at own cleverness or is frustrated
when unable to do something.

2EA284243527471597D6E4D4CDFE96F9.description:
Shows distress when preferred people
don’t interact with them.

D3A58F92C912481FBACB0D5073E1D0D2.description:
Uses name to refer to significant people;
for example, “Mama” or Papa”.

978A97613BE54C10918994F544B62DBF.description:
Recognizes familiar people in addition to
immediate family or primary caregiver.

85CEBF25353A45678C4C0E6D39B558BE.description:
Begins to recognize and respond to own
name (example: gestures at sound of
name or vocalizes at sound of name).

E2297561172949819304C913CD992C4D.description:
Express thoughts and feelings by saying
“no!”

8C9A305F879C4611B20B0EA9E8A26054.description:
Points to or indicates parts of the body
when asked.

3327E1C14C9E4C2B9C075FBD3C063C03.description:
Shows preferences; cries when
something is not liked.

A3E04084086741C3A5F45BAE41826388.description:
Recognizes, holds, touches own feet and
hands.

9B47722B799C46C6AAF31D0593CBFAB8.description:
Cries when a parent or caregiver leaves
the room.

4BDDD044816B466186EC17EB8C08A58A.description:
Beginning to understand that they can
make things happen; (example: pat a
musical toy to make music come again,
or raise arms to be picked up by parent
or caregiver).

D92A8C4210C2406FBCD5A854476034C3.description:
Uses hands to explore different parts of
the body.

05B8B638108D438295F62CD11808AC57.description: Sense of Self, Self-Awareness, and Self-Concept

A2D0AAD6CB154B9D8C7276CD5E1F992C.description:
let’s a trusted adult know when
hungry, tired or needing assistance
with a peer

5A975A42409C41B1A924BB6430A7A5FD.description:
using words or signs such as “no” or
“stop” during conflict

E625205FA1344C1CBA3E0424C6259966.description:
Begins to manage and adjust actions and
behavior with the guidance of familiar
adults:

4BE742905B064E0C8DEB28CB2939C5CD.description:
begins to dress themselves as part
of daily routines, even though it may
take longer

50F6891344F2404EBAD5951B03E17561.description:
joins group time for dancing, stories,
etc.

B5759BF3AF65495BBE03840C0D9BC102.description: gets ready to go for a walk

59FF4B1B7BD14557AE68245AED1B8D5A.description:
anticipates and follows routines when
prompted:

5B05830F728C407DB28FE158858AC0CC.description:
tolerating brief wait times or
delays

1274826D083243DD915EFFC3F1A418B7.description:
beginning to understand their role
in play (need to wait for a turn for a
toy)

CB702ACBD31E4651B13CCC1BDF6E327E.description:
Can be restless and determined creating
conflicted needs which can lead to
power struggles emerging (Example:
child is tired but doesn’t want to stop
playing).

A3F253ED0A8048ECB0A56F879A3DD623.description:
Anticipates and participates in routine
activities:

0A8F26D3337A45A8B5ACABC30BFDD9CD.description:
utilizing quiet space in classroom
when needed

254A82C14B1B4B5D9B7F628F43606A22.description:
wants to be put down – squirms,
pushes away

138654CC6D8744629FB316706BC60B6A.description:
Starts, maintains, or stops social contact
through:

2799848758164B47801A858EF1752317.description:
Has an expectation that the caregiver will
provide what is needed in most situations.

2AA6AB89D1DA4F11BA08EA59C26097C7.description:
Begins to express feelings of anger and
frustration: tells friends “I don’t like that!”.

EE68115AFB424641B5BE1784C29D98DA.description:
Expresses empathy toward other children or
adults.

9C3EE63BA9FF4B42BB16ED35414755F9.description:
May use artistic tools for emotional
expression.

81E9D307D5CD44A0ABB4F6657D2C99D3.description:
Shows understanding of some emotional
expressions by

27510E6A397745AC94EFDC4931910004.description:
Self-conscious emotions appear: shame,
embarrassment, guilt, pride.

02D5847DB8E443A09B18FD7B7C0957B4.description:
Displays confidence that needs will be met
by caregiver, evidenced by child watching
and waiting a short time for caregiver to
meet the recognized need.

8873A011DE5F4B01ABAEB7B568C42616.description:
looks sad or concerned when another
child is crying; may offer soft toy,
blanket, or food

0FD14F4BDF314278AA840304B4FA4BE0.description:
sharing emotional reactions – smiling
when adult smiles, showing excitement
when other children are excited

45BA3B977AAE49488BA74B3919B5D910.description:
Responds to others’ emotional expressions
by:

AC053A1221C24312895ECF9052DD44AB.description:
Looks to/seeks comfort from familiar adults
when distressed and accepts reassurance.

E28927DA288243E89EA7EEC1BE9051A3.description:
Expresses a variety of emotions and
modifies expression according to the
reactions of familiar adults.

E1581AE854924E4BBA6E1923E0C7CAD9.description: May cry when another child cries

81CCD9CFE0744D8BBB8D4A5331D67CE3.description:
Attends with interest when others
show range of emotions through facial
expressions, voices, or gestures.

86E58AEE2BB84C96A84B1AE3C18EAEE0.description:
Quiets or stops crying when held, rocked,
given a change of position or level of
stimulation in the environment, or talked to
by a familiar adult.

DD1D2A37DFF84EB5B9ABE8264E18C5A7.description:
Expresses feelings of comfort, discomfort,
enjoyment, fear, surprise, anger or
unhappiness through:
